        "id": 272519,
        "name": "ðŸ‘ŠðŸ‡ºðŸ‡¸ðŸ”¥",
        "username": "Avitus",
        "avatar_template": "/user_avatar/community.signalusers.org/avitus/{size}/34172_2.png",
        "created_at": "2025-07-25T13:24:37.733Z",
        "cooked": "<aside class=\"quote no-group\" data-username=\"jbolger\" data-post=\"1\" data-topic=\"70636\">\n<div class=\"title\">\n<div class=\"quote-controls\"></div>\n<img alt=\"\" width=\"24\" height=\"24\" src=\"https://community.signalusers.org/letter_avatar_proxy/v4/letter/j/c5a1d2/48.png\" class=\"avatar\"> jbolger:</div>\n<blockquote>\n<p>The undelivered messages will queue up on Signalâ€™s servers for days, weeks, months perhaps. But there is no actual need for these messages to continue residing on Signalâ€™s servers since the user does not want or expect their delivery. The user will accumulate risk probably without even realizing a discreet remote archive of their chat history is building (albeit encrypted).</p>\n</blockquote>\n</aside>\n<p>Queued messages are purged from the server after 14 days.</p>\n<aside class=\"quote no-group\" data-username=\"jbolger\" data-post=\"1\" data-topic=\"70636\">\n<div class=\"title\">\n<div class=\"quote-controls\"></div>\n<img alt=\"\" width=\"24\" height=\"24\" src=\"https://community.signalusers.org/letter_avatar_proxy/v4/letter/j/c5a1d2/48.png\" class=\"avatar\"> jbolger:</div>\n<blockquote>\n<p>The primary device Signal app will be practically unusable for hours upon using it for the first time in months, as the app will proceed to download and decrypt perhaps thousands of messages that have accumulated in that time.</p>\n</blockquote>\n</aside>\n<p>This scenario is highly unlikely. The old time-to-live for queued messages was 30 days, but was changed to 14 days a few years ago.</p>\n<p>In any case, there is an existing request this fits into:</p>\n<aside class=\"quote quote-modified\" data-post=\"1\" data-topic=\"70637\">\n  <div class=\"title\">\n    <div class=\"quote-controls\"></div>\n    <img alt=\"\" width=\"24\" height=\"24\" src=\"https://community.signalusers.org/letter_avatar_proxy/v4/letter/j/c5a1d2/48.png\" class=\"avatar\">\n    <a href=\"https://community.signalusers.org/t/desktop-app-as-primary-device/70637\">Desktop App as Primary Device</a> <a class=\"badge-category__wrapper \" href=\"/c/feature-requests/desktop-feature-requests/20\"><span data-category-id=\"20\" style=\"--category-badge-color: #2D8B39; --category-badge-text-color: #FFFFFF; --parent-category-badge-color: #83B72A;\" data-parent-category-id=\"17\" data-drop-close=\"true\" class=\"badge-category --has-parent\"><span class=\"badge-category__name\">Desktop Feature Requests</span></span></a>\n  </div>\n  <blockquote>\n    The Desktop app should not be relegated to a second-class position in the Signal ecosystem.  The Desktop app should be capable of registering a Signal account and becoming a Signal accountâ€™s primary device just like its smartphone app counterparts.  There is no technical or security justification for this arbitrary limitation, and it does more harm than good to Signal in general, by making Signal less accessible to users with limited access, limited use case, or limited financial resources, for â€¦\n  </blockquote>\n</aside>\n\n<p>Now that linked devices sync history, the simple solution to your scenario is to unlink devices you donâ€™t want to receive messages when you donâ€™t need them to.</p>",
